:''Not to be confused with [[Meige syndrome]]''
In [[medicine]], '''Meigs syndrome''', also '''Meigs' syndrome''', is the triad of [[ascites]], [[pleural effusion]] and benign [[ovarian tumor]] ([[fibroma]], [[Brenner tumour]] and occasionally [[granulosa cell tumour]]).<ref>{{EMedicine|article|255450|Meigs syndrome}}</ref><ref name="pmid16515612">{{cite journal |author=Morán-Mendoza A, Alvarado-Luna G, Calderillo-Ruiz G, Serrano-Olvera A, López-Graniel CM, Gallardo-Rincón D |title=Elevated CA125 level associated with Meigs' syndrome: case report and review of the literature |journal=Int. J. Gynecol. Cancer |volume=16 |issue=Suppl 1 |pages=315–318 |year=2006 |pmid=16515612 |doi=10.1111/j.1525-1438.2006.00228.x}}</ref><ref name=shaw>{{cite book|last=Padubidri, Daftary|title=Shaw's Textbook Of Gynaecology, 15e|publisher=Elsevier India|isbn=9788131225486|page=385}}</ref>   It resolves after the [[Segmental resection|resection]] of the [[tumor]].  Because the transdiaphragmatic lymphatic channels are larger in diameter on the right, the pleural effusion is classically on the right side. The etiologies of the ascites and pleural effusion are poorly understood.<ref>{{EMedicine|article|255450|Meigs syndrome}}</ref>
==Differential diagnosis==
It may mimic other conditions.<ref name="pmid19161612">{{cite journal |author=Lanitis S, Sivakumar S, Behranwala K, Zacharakis E, Al Mufti R, Hadjiminas DJ |title=A case of Meigs syndrome mimicking metastatic breast carcinoma |journal=World J Surg Oncol |volume=7 |pages=10 |year=2009 |pmid=19161612 |pmc=2633000 |doi=10.1186/1477-7819-7-10 |url=http://www.wjso.com/content/7//10}}</ref>

Because of the presence of ascites and transudative pleural effusions, the [[differential diagnosis]] includes [[liver failure]] ([[cirrhosis]]), [[congestive heart failure]], [[renal disease]]s, and [[metastatic tumor]]s to the peritoneal surfaces.  These entities must be clinically excluded.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}

==Treatment==
Treatment of Meigs' syndrome consists of [[thoracentesis]] and [[paracentesis]] to drain off the excess fluid (transudate), and unilateral [[oophorectomy|salpingo-oophorectomy]] or wedge resection to correct the underlying [[etiology]].

==Eponym==
'''Meigs' Syndrome''' is named for [[Joe Vincent Meigs]].<ref>{{WhoNamedIt|synd|2351|Meigs' syndrome}}</ref><ref name="pmid10996681">{{cite journal |author=Lurie S |title=Meigs' syndrome: the history of the eponym |journal=Eur. J. Obstet. Gynecol. Reprod. Biol. |volume=92 |issue=2 |pages=199–204 |year=2000 |pmid=10996681 |doi= 10.1016/S0301-2115(99)00289-4|url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0301211599002894}}</ref><ref name="pmid13148256">{{cite journal |author=Meigs JV |title=Fibroma of the ovary with ascites and hydrothorax; Meigs' syndrome |journal=Am. J. Obstet. Gynecol. |volume=67 |issue=5 |pages=962–85 |year=1954 |month=May |pmid=13148256 }}</ref>

